\begin{abstract}
We investigate Topological Integrity Gravity (TIG) as a constrained quadratic $f(R)$ extension of General Relativity. 
The model exhibits a structurally controlled transition in horizon formation governed by a dimensionless critical parameter $\beta_c$.

We derive the horizon structure analytically and analyze modifications in photon-sphere geometry, quasi-normal-mode spectra, and echo signatures. 
Near the critical regime, nonlinear deviations from Schwarzschild behavior emerge, leading to frequency shifts and parametrically enhanced echo delays.

These features provide potential observational signatures in gravitational-wave and black hole imaging data.
\end{abstract}

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Introduction}

General Relativity remains the foundation of modern gravitational physics \cite{Einstein1915,Wald1984}. 
Among its extensions, $f(R)$ gravity provides a minimal framework for incorporating higher-curvature corrections \cite{Sotiriou2010,DeFelice2010}. 
Quadratic curvature corrections are particularly important due to their relation to Starobinsky gravity \cite{Starobinsky1980}.

In this work, we study a constrained quadratic $f(R)$ model that exhibits a critical transition in horizon formation. 
Unlike purely phenomenological regular black hole constructions such as Bardeen- or Hayward-type models \cite{Bardeen1968,Hayward2006}, this transition is characterized by an analytic critical parameter controlling the existence of horizons.

The resulting geometry leads to modified photon-sphere structure, quasi-normal-mode behavior, and possible echo signatures. These effects connect the model to observational probes including black hole imaging and gravitational-wave ringdown measurements \cite{Berti2009,Cardoso2016,Cardoso2019,Abbott2016,EHT2019}.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Formalism}

We consider the action
\begin{equation}
S = \int d^4x \sqrt{-g}
\left[
\frac{1}{16\pi}(R - 2\Lambda) + \alpha R^2
\right]
+ S_{\mathrm{matter}}.
\end{equation}

Defining
\begin{equation}
f(R) = R - 2\Lambda + \mu R^2,
\quad
\mu = 16\pi\alpha,
\end{equation}
the model corresponds to quadratic $f(R)$ gravity.

\subsection{Scalar Degree of Freedom}

Quadratic $f(R)$ gravity contains an additional scalar curvature degree of freedom. We define
\begin{equation}
\phi = f'(R) = 1 + 2\mu R.
\end{equation}

The corresponding effective scalar mass is
\begin{equation}
m_\phi^2 = \frac{1}{3f''(R)} = \frac{1}{6\mu}.
\end{equation}

For $\mu>0$, this mode is non-tachyonic, supporting perturbative consistency of the quadratic correction \cite{DeFelice2010,Sotiriou2010}.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Field Equations}

The modified field equations are
\begin{equation}
f'(R)R_{\mu\nu}
-\frac{1}{2}f(R)g_{\mu\nu}
-\nabla_\mu\nabla_\nu f'(R)
+g_{\mu\nu}\Box f'(R)
=
8\pi T_{\mu\nu}.
\end{equation}

The trace equation is
\begin{equation}
3\Box f'(R)+f'(R)R-2f(R)=8\pi T.
\end{equation}

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Static Configurations}

We consider static, spherically symmetric geometries of the form
\begin{equation}
ds^2
=
-F(r)dt^2
+
\frac{dr^2}{F(r)}
+
r^2 d\Omega^2.
\end{equation}

\subsection{Effective Interior Profile}

We adopt the effective mass profile
\begin{equation}
m(r)=\frac{Mr^3}{r^3+r_c^3}.
\end{equation}

The corresponding metric function is
\begin{equation}
F(r)=1-\frac{2m(r)}{r}.
\end{equation}

This metric should be interpreted as an effective ansatz capturing qualitative features of regularized compact objects in modified gravity.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Horizon Structure}

Horizons satisfy
\begin{equation}
F(r_H)=0.
\end{equation}

Substitution of the mass profile gives
\begin{equation}
r_H^3-2Mr_H^2+r_c^3=0.
\end{equation}

Introducing dimensionless variables
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{r_H}{2M},
\quad
\beta=\frac{r_c}{2M},
\end{equation}
we obtain
\begin{equation}
x^3-x^2+\beta^3=0.
\end{equation}

\subsection{Critical Transition}

The cubic equation admits a real positive horizon solution only up to the critical value
\begin{equation}
\beta_c=\left(\frac{4}{27}\right)^{1/3}.
\end{equation}

For $\beta\leq\beta_c$, horizon-bearing configurations exist. For $\beta>\beta_c$, no positive horizon solution remains.

\subsection{Deviation from Schwarzschild}

Near the Schwarzschild regime, the outer horizon branch can be expanded as
\begin{equation}
x\simeq 1-\beta^3+\mathcal{O}(\beta^6),
\end{equation}
so that
\begin{equation}
r_H\simeq 2M(1-\beta^3).
\end{equation}

