\section{Photon Sphere and Shadow Radius}

The photon sphere is determined by
\begin{equation}
rF'(r)-2F(r)=0.
\end{equation}

The corresponding shadow radius is
\begin{equation}
R_{\mathrm{sh}}
=
\frac{r_{\mathrm{ph}}}{\sqrt{F(r_{\mathrm{ph}})}}.
\end{equation}

Near the critical regime, deviations in the photon-sphere structure can translate into observable deviations in shadow size.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Perturbative Dynamics}

Perturbations may be described at the level of the radial scattering problem by a Schrödinger-like master equation
\begin{equation}
\frac{d^2\Psi}{dr_*^2}
+
\left[
\omega^2-V_{\mathrm{eff}}(r)
\right]\Psi
=0,
\end{equation}
where the tortoise coordinate is defined by
\begin{equation}
\frac{dr_*}{dr}
=
\frac{1}{F(r)}.
\end{equation}

The following analysis uses approximate methods to capture qualitative spectral behavior.

\subsection{Eikonal QNM Approximation}

In the eikonal approximation, the quasi-normal-mode spectrum is controlled by the photon-sphere frequency and its instability timescale \cite{Berti2009}. We write
\begin{equation}
\omega_{\ell n}
\simeq
\left(\ell+\frac{1}{2}\right)\Omega_{\mathrm{ph}}
-
i\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)\lambda_{\mathrm{ph}}.
\end{equation}

Near the critical regime, the increasing redshift produces a softening of the real part of the spectrum and a reduced damping rate:
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Re}(\omega)\downarrow,
\quad
|\mathrm{Im}(\omega)|\downarrow.
\end{equation}

