\subsection{Waveform Model}

A phenomenological waveform may be written as
\begin{equation}
h(t)
=
h_{\mathrm{ringdown}}(t)
+
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}
A_n
e^{-i\omega(t-n\Delta t)}
\Theta(t-n\Delta t).
\end{equation}

This represents a primary ringdown followed by delayed echo contributions.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Observational Implications}

The model predicts three observational channels:

\begin{itemize}
\item deviations in black hole shadow radius,
\item systematic shifts in quasi-normal-mode frequencies,
\item possible echo signatures in gravitational-wave ringdown.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Comparison with GW150914}

The fundamental ringdown frequency observed in GW150914 is of order \cite{Abbott2016}
\begin{equation}
M\omega\sim 0.37-0.09i.
\end{equation}

The representative TIG values remain comparable for small $\beta$, while deviations grow as the critical regime is approached. This suggests that TIG effects, if present, would appear as systematic corrections rather than large departures from General Relativity.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Stability}

For $\mu>0$, the scalar degree of freedom is non-tachyonic. This is consistent with the standard stability requirements of viable $f(R)$ theories \cite{DeFelice2010,Sotiriou2010}.

A full perturbative stability analysis remains future work.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Relation to General Relativity and Regular Black Hole Models}

In the limit $\beta\to 0$, the geometry reduces to Schwarzschild spacetime.

For finite $\beta$, the geometry resembles regular black hole models in that the central singularity is replaced by a regular core. However, the present construction emphasizes an analytic critical transition in horizon formation, distinguishing it from purely phenomenological regular black hole metrics \cite{Bardeen1968,Hayward2006}.

%--------------------------------------------------

\section{Conclusion}

We identified a critical parameter
\begin{equation}
\beta_c=\left(\frac{4}{27}\right)^{1/3}
\end{equation}
governing horizon formation in a constrained quadratic $f(R)$ model.

This transition affects both geometry and perturbative dynamics, producing potential observational signatures in black hole imaging and gravitational-wave data.

Future work should address full numerical quasi-normal-mode spectra, waveform generation, and direct comparison with observational datasets.

